    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "o38VQkcdKd6k"
      },
      "source": [
        "# 2 Problem formulation\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "This project addresses the machine learning problem of song classification using 'amateur' attempts at producing musical audio in the form of hums and whistles. A model is trained to predict the song label of variable length recordings, trimmed to 10 seconds during preprocessing, in which participants hum or whistle one of these 8 recognised songs:\n",
        "\n",
        "- Happy\n",
        "- Feeling\n",
        "- NewYork\n",
        "- RememberMe\n",
        "- Friend\n",
        "- Married\n",
        "- Necessities\n",
        "- TryEverything\n",
        "\n",
        "The input is a raw audio file, with the output being a discrete class label corresponding to one of the songs listed above. This constitutes a supervised multiclass classification problem.\n",
        "\n",
        "The difficulty lies in the gap between what a classifier receives and the features that usually make aid classification. As there are no lyrics used, that strips away a highly distinctive identifying feature. This leaves only a very rough outline, which is made even more challenging to decipher by the fact that individuals vary in vocal style, pitch accuracy, intonation, tempo and many more other such aspects.\n",
        "\n",
        "This is a known problem for big-tech developers like Google, who tackle the same problem of musical classification in their Hum to Search feature. As mentioned over years, a hummed tune contains significantly less information to assist in correct classification than that of a studio recording (Frank, 2020) making traditional ML classification a difficult task. This project addresses these issues under realistic auditory environments, using machine learning methods and a dataset (ever so slightly!) more limited than Google's."
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "bPTSuaB9L2jU"
      },
      "source": [
        "---\n",
        "# 3 Methodology\n",
        "\n",
        "Using training data recordings, the goal is to build a machine learning model that is able to most effectively generalise to the unseen (test) data. In following a deployment-first view, the 'best' model in this instance is defined not as the one with the lowest training error, but as the one with the highest estimated deployment quality. A model might perform well on training data, but then perform poorly on unseen data because it has simply memorised the specifics of the training set, as opposed to learning how to classify patterns ,thereby overfitting the model.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "The task is split into 3 distinct phases:\n",
        "1. Training\n",
        "2. Validation\n",
        "3. Testing\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "## 3.1 Training\n",
        "\n",
        "During training, a classifier is trained on a subset of the data. It takes a fixed-length feature vector extracted from each audio file and uses that to output a predicted song label. This phase is used to tune the model's parameters in order to minimise errors on the training data.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "## 3.2 Validation\n",
        "\n",
        "Next, a dataset separate from the training data, called the validation dataset, is used to compare different pipelines. These pipelines can include different features and model bodies. Within this project, the validation set is also used for hyperparameter tuning  (selecting the best value of k for kNN, max_depth for Random Forest, and C for SVM) by comparing performance over multiple combinations and selecting the one with the highest validation accuracy.\n",
        "\n",
        "Since the validation dataset hasn't been 'seen' during training, its performance is presented as a reliable estimate of the deployment quality, thus helping us choose the most effective model for testing.\n",
        "\n",
        "In the real world, the cost of a model can also be a key factor in this choice (small improvements in metrics are not always worth a vast difference in  cost). However, as this is a personal project, the most suitable model is selected based primarily on performance metrics.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "## 3.3 Testing\n",
        "\n",
        "Finally, the test dataset is utilised. This has been kept completely separate throughout the entire process, as using it in any form beforehand would be data leakage and would compromise it as an honest estimate of deployment performance. It is used only once, after the final model selection stage, to produce a final quality estimate. To go against this and tune the training or validation process after  would create data leakage and result in an overly optimistic, biased estimate of how the model will actually perform.\n",
        "\n",
        "A formal test set is implemented using a participant-based three way split. 70% of participants for training, 20% for validation and 10% for the test. This is designed to approximate IID conditions by ensuring that each set is drawn from an independent subset of participants, with no participant appearing across more than a single set.\n",
        "\n",
        "The test set is used at the end of Section 6, after all model selection and hyperparameter tuning has been complete, to produce a final honest deployment estimate. The reasoning behind this split, and why it is only applied to one of the three datasets, is discussed in Section 3.4 below.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "## 3.4 Dataset Split\n",
        "\n",
        "A key portion of consideration was in the dataset split, as this decision is arguably one of the most important in the pipeline for final quality. The split determines what the model learns from as well as ultimately how honest the performance estimate is of real deployment conditions. These splits and performance metrics were thus defined before training of models, as recommended to avoid adjustments in hindsight and forms of confirmation bias (Kapoor and Narayanan, 2023).\n",
        "\n",
        "Three splits are explored, which get progressively more stricter:\n",
        "\n",
        "> Dataset A - random stratified 80/20 split. This is the simplest split, and just randomly splits the sample set into 80% for training and 20% validation. It maximises the training data but risks participant leakage between the training and validation sets.\n",
        "\n",
        "> Dataset B - attempt-based split. Attempts 1 & 3 go to training, while attempts 2 & 4 to validation. This ensures that no exact recording appears in both. The 1+3 vs 2+4 grouping is deliberate, as verified in Section 5.2, as attempts 3 and 4 contain only hums, so this split ensures both training and validation sets contain a mix of interpretation types. However, participants whose vocal characteristics are consistent across attempts may still introduce some leakage.\n",
        "\n",
        "> Dataset C - participant-based split. Within this split, no participant appears in more than one set in any form, making it the strictest and most honest of the three splits to real deployment conditions. This is precisely why it is the only split extended to a three way 70/20/10 train/validation/test configuration as outlined in Section 3.3. Datasets A and B serve solely as model comparison splits, allowing the observational analysis of how increasing strict generalisation conditions may affect model performance.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Dataset sizes, distributions and visualisations are further developed in Section 5.2.*\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "## 3.5 Performance\n",
        "\n",
        "The performances of the models are quantified using the overall accuracy rates within a confusion matrix. The overall accuracy (proportion of correctly classified samples) provides a summary. However, as we are dealing with 8 different song classes, the overall accuracy is not sufficient by itself, as a classifier could perform well on the very *'distinct from the other'* songs, while failing for another, and this wouldnt be visible in a single figure.\n",
        "\n",
        "With the confusion matrix, we will be able to see how predictions are distributed across each class, including per-class accuracies on the diagonal and patterns of misclassifications on the off-diagonal (Scikit-learn developers, 2024). This is meaningful to find as it can reveal musical similarity between the songs, rather than the model error alone, showing us why it has been misclassified.\n",
        "\n",
        "A random classifier operating across 8 equally distributed classes could achieve an expected accuracy of 12.5% just through mere chance, in the exact way that any outcome is theoretically possible through random chance given enough attempts, as theorised by the Infinite Monkey Theorem.  Thus, all results are interpreted against this baseline with accuracy above this threshold, an indicator that the model has extracted some distinctive tells from the features even if overall performance remains modest.\n"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "N3BwrtEdLDit"
      },
      "source": [
        "---\n",
        "# 4 Implemented ML prediction pipelines\n",
        "\n",
        "As briefly discussed earlier, the prediction pipeline takes a raw audio file as input and produces a discrete song label class as output. There is, however, a transformation phase that takes place in between that makes this classification process more manageable.\n",
        "\n",
        "By summarising each audio file into a feature vector (a small set of numbers representing relevant attributes of the melody), the dimensionality of the problem is reduced considerably, and the classifier can recognise the song by analysing these feature vectors, as opposed to thousands of individual data points. This vector is then normalised and passed to the classifier, with the full pipeline pictured below:\n"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "![Pipeline - canva.png](data:image/png;base64,)"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "hXp27NALvtsd"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "\n",
        "*(Image created using Canva)*\n",
        "\n",
        "This is a supervised pipeline, whereby every recording in the training set has a respective recognised song label, and the model learns to map feature vectors to these labels.\n",
        "\n",
        "One thing that is crucial to note here is that the entire pipeline is what is trained and subsequently deployed, not the model. So the quality of the final prediction depends on every single stage of this pipeline, and a change to any stage requires the subsequent model to be retrained accordingly.\n",
        "\n",
        "This project evaluates 59 pipeline combinations in total:\n",
        "- 5 models x 3 dataset splits = 15 base pipelines\n",
        "\n",
        "- kNN k selection: 9 values tested on Dataset A = 9\n",
        "- Random Forest depth exploration: 6 depths x 3 datasets = 18\n",
        "- MFCC coefficient tuning: 3 values (13, 20, 40) = 3\n",
        "- SVM C parameter tuning: 6 values (0.1, 0.5, 1, 5, 10, 100) = 6\n",
        "- Ensemble variants: 5 model, curated 3 model, curated 2 model across datasets = 5\n",
        "- Ablation study feature subsets = 3\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "The stages are described as follows:"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "lwWrpykxvxvq"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "j1nDXnzYLLH6"
      },
      "source": [
        "## 4.1 Transformation stage\n",
        "\n",
        "INPUT: The raw audio file.\n",
        "\n",
        "> E.g: hum_1_[Married].wav\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "OUTPUT: A feature vector number value for each recording, that consists of concatenated power/pitch features, MFCCs and chroma coefficients.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "> E.g: [0.003, 176.3, 44.0, -43.0, 0.34...]\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "The raw audio is an example of 'grid data', such that the grid is 1D and a discrete sequence of values recorded across the time axis. As the default 'librosa' sampling rate is 22,050 hz (Starter kit) , with a 10-second recording, this would mean 10 x 22,050 = 220,500 values. This would be extremely impractical to actually conduct in practice, as well as very prone to overfitting, so instead, a feature extraction is applied here to reduce the dimensionality to a more compact depiction.\n",
        "\n",
        "Prior to feature extraction, each recording is trimmed to a fixed duration of 10 seconds, to maintain consistency across all audio files using a 'duration' parameter:\n",
        "\n",
        "`x, fs = librosa.load(file, sr=None, duration=10.0)`\n",
        "\n",
        "Initially, only 4 features provided are considered: power, pitch mean, pitch standard deviation, and voiced fraction.. Upon reflection however, it becomes clear that pitch and energy features simply do not carry enough for melodic classification, since two entirely different songs could share similar pitch ranges and levels when hummed by the same person. This initiates the addition of some more nuanced features, specifically MFCCs (Davis and Mermelstein, 1980) and chroma (Müller, 2015), which help to capture more of the melodic and timbral flow of the recordings, extracted using librosa.\n",
        "\n",
        "It is worth noting that at scale, Google's Hum to Search system does not use features like MFCCs entirely, instead training a neural network to produce embeddings directly from spectrograms (Frank, 2020). Due to the fact that Google operates on a considerably larger database of songs with availability to vast training data, a neural netowrk was certainly most appropriate. This ML project on the other hand, works within the constraints of 800 recordings hence the use of classical machine learning methods.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "The following features are extracted from each audio file using the librosa library:\n",
        "\n",
        ">1. Pitch means\n",
        "2. Pitch standard deviations\n",
        "3. Power\n",
        "4. Voiced fraction\n",
        "\n",
        "Together, these 4 provide a starter for the melodic summary of each recording, and do well to present a general baseline against which the value of the additional spectral features can be assessed.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        ">MFCCs - n=13, tuned from 13/20/40\n",
        "\n",
        "Mel-frequency cepstral coefficients capture the timbral and spectral shape of the signal compactly (Davis and Mermelstein, 1980). Each recording produces 13 MFCC values averaged across time, reducing the audio to a fixed length vector compatible with the classifier. The number of coefficients in it was treated as a hyperparameter and tuned, later discussed within Section 6.3 where n=13 was found to be optimal out of the three.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        ">Chroma features (12 features)\n",
        "\n",
        "Chroma features summarise the pitch content of a recording across 12 frequency bands, and captures information about the melodic structure of the audio that goes with the information provided by the MFCCs (Müller, 2015).These are also averaged across time, producing 12 values per recording.\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "The final feature vector for each recording is the concatenation of all 3 of these above groups:\n",
        "\n",
        "> 4 (power/pitch) + 13 (MFCCs) + 12 (chroma) = 29 features per recording\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "Following the feature extraction transformation, all features are to be standardised using the z-score normalisation, fitted on the training set, and applied to both validation and test sets.\n",
        "\n",
        "This is crucial because the 29 features all operate on varied numerical scales and can differ massively between one another, so scaling is necessary. Once again, we have to be very wary for the full pipeline stage and it's important to note that models like kNN where distances are key, can be extremely sensitive to unnormalised features. With 29 features and approximately 560 training samples in Dataset C, the sample to feature ratio is approximatelt 15:1, which, is sufficient enough to avoid severe overfitting from parameter excess.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "To assess the contribution each of these feature groups has had overall, an ablation study is conducted in Section 6.6 to test the assumption that adding features improves performance, or if it is only adding noise."
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "0F5_kI95LuZ2"
      },
      "source": [
        "## 4.2 Model stage\n",
        "\n",
        "INPUT: Normalised feature vector per audio file.\n",
        "\n",
        "> E.g: [1.23, 2.3, 0.45, 0.7…]\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "OUTPUT: Predicted song label from one of the 8 classes.\n",
        "\n",
        "> E.g: Married\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "Within the model stage, 5 model families are to be explored. The main principle driving the selection process is the flexibility to interpretability trade-off. While simpler models might be easier to understand, they lack a certain level of complexity required to most effectively capture the crucial patterns from the data. Whereas the more flexible models do tend to run a risk of overfitting, especially when there is a (somewhat) limited dataset. In exploring multiple models, we can assess whether an increased level of complexity does actually improve generalisation, or not.\n",
        "\n",
        "The most simple, as well as easily interpretable of the 5 models is Logistic Regression. It produces a linear decision boundary in the feature space and is included here as a baseline. If a linear boundary is sufficient to separate the song classes, more complex models are essentially unnecessary. However, we predict this will not be the case given the high intra-class variability (different people humming the same song can sound very different) and the low inter-class variability between some classes (similar sounding songs might overlap in sections of the feature space), a linear boundary alone is unlikely to be sufficient. The model is optimised using gradient descent, with a maximum of 1000 iterations set to ensure the optimisation completes:\n",
        "\n",
        "`model_lr_A = LogisticRegression(max_iter=1000)`\n",
        "\n",
        "A following model, the k-Nearest Neighbour (kNN) assigns each new sample the label of the majority class among its nearest neighbours in the feature space. Unlike logistic regression, kNN produces a non-linear decision boundary and its complexity decreases as k increases. Overfitting can be likely with a low value for k, and underfitting at a large value, so it is important to select an appropriate value for k, determined through validation across a range of values. This model does not require any explicit training phase, as it memorises the training set and computes distances according to the feature space. This makes it quite sensitive to the normalisation stage, as features with larger values could dominate the distance calculations.\n",
        "\n",
        "Another model is the Support Vector Machine (SVM), which looks for the decision boundaries that maximise the margins between classes in the feature space. A radial basis function kernel is used here, which allows SVM to produce non-linear boundaries, which is useful given the expected intra-class variability in the data (Scikit-learn developers, 2024). SVM tends to work well for smaller datasets, which works in our favour here.\n",
        "\n",
        "Another model used is the Naive Bayes classifier. Which is a probabilistic classifier that applies Bayes' rule and estimates the posterior probability of each class from the class priors and class conditional densities. However, important to note here, Naive bayes makes the assumption that all the features are independent given the class labels. But this assumption is almost certainly violated in our case as MFCC coefficients describe overlapping frequency characteristics of the same audio signal, meaning they naturally influence each other and cannot be treated as independent, per se. We can still explore its use as a model anyway because in assuming that it will underperform compared to the other models, it works well for the sake of our analysis, and can actually provide an interesting angle to our findings about the result of violated independence assumptions in practice.\n",
        "\n",
        "Finally, Random Forest is an ensemble of decision trees, each trained on a random subset of training samples and features, with predictions obtained by majority vote across all trees. It is more flexible than Logistic Regression while being less prone to overfitting than a single decision tree. Though, depth constraints are still required to prevent overfitting in practice, as explored in Section 6.2. Given the expected non-linear relationship between spectral features and song labels, Random Forest is expected to be among the stronger individual models here.\n",
        "\n",
        "Across the 5 models, the complexity of the decision boundaries increases from Logistic Regression (which produces linear boundaries) to Random Forest (which produces highly non-linear ones) with SVM, kNN and Naive Bayes sitting in between. Comparing their performance across the 3 dataset splits mentioned earlier allows us to assess which model performs the best as well as any pattern of results which will reveal another aspect to the nature of the problem itself.\n",
        "\n",
        "The outputs of all five models are combined in Section 4.3."
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "89VeK89DQn5y"
      },
      "source": [
        "## 4.3 Ensemble stage\n",
        "\n",
        "INPUT: Predicted labels from all five models for each recording.\n",
        "\n",
        "> E.g: ['Married', 'Married', 'RememberMe', 'Married', 'Married']\n",
        "\n",
        "OUTPUT: Predicted song label from one of the 8 classes.\n",
        "\n",
        "> E.g: Married\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "The final stage will involve the ensemble approach which involves combining the predictions from all 5 of the models to use a majority vote strategy. The predicted label that received the most votes across the five models is taken then as the final prediction.\n",
        "\n",
        "The motivation for the ensemble approach is that each model likely captures a different aspect of the audio's patterns. Logistic regression might find a broad linear separator in the feature space, while kNN might identify nearby clusters. Also, SVM could find the widest possible margins between classes as initially mentioned, and Random Forests can capture a more complex non-linear relation. Thus, in combining their outputs there is a hope that the weaknesses evident from each individual model are blurred out by the effect of the strengths from the other ones, wishfully speaking.\n",
        "\n",
        "The ensemble does not require any additional training beyond the 5 individual models.\n",
        "\n",
        "If the five models are making similar errors for example, all struggling to distinguish Married from RememberMe, then combining them will not exactly help. However, if their errors are sufficiently distinct, the ensemble should outperform any single model. This is discussed further in Section 6 in light of the results."
      ]
    },
