    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "The dataset is perfectly balanced with 100 recordings per song class, 400 hums and 400 whistles, meaning that class imbalance is not a concern here.\n",
        "\n",
        "There are 187 unique participants, each contributing multiple recordings. The dataset is a *sample* of the full MLEnd Hums and Whistles II dataset, so not all participants contributed recordings of every song. Attempt numbers are distributed unevenly across the sample (approximately 348 for attempt 1, 322 for attempt 2, 64 for attempt 3 and 66 for attempt 4), which directly explains why Dataset B produces a smaller training set of only 412 samples.\n",
        "\n",
        "An 80/20 ratio is used across splits A and B as it maximises the amount of data available for training while storing enough samples in validation to produce a reliable estimate. Dataset C is the only split which has a three part 70/20/10 (train/validation/test) configuration, for the reasons discussed earlier in Section 3.4.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "#### Limitations:\n",
        "\n",
        "Many participants will have multiple recordings within the sample, and they are not independent, as these might share the same vocal manner, pitch and/or background noises.\n",
        "\n",
        "A random split risks placing the recordings from the same participants in both the training and validation, which might in turn produce an overly optimistic estimate of deployment performance. This was the main reason for exploration of further dataset splits, to address this exact limitation.\n",
        "\n",
        "Additionally, the dataset is relatively small at 800 samples across 8 classes, and approx. 100 samples per class. Which limits the complexity of the models that can be trained without overfitting, and it means that validation accuracy estimates are more uncertain, given the even smaller than the training set, validation set sizes."
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "x4Q7cTWbOAUY"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "## 5.2 Dataset Splits\n",
        "\n",
        "As outlined within Section 3 above, three datasets were split to represent  progressively  stricter conditions of generalisation. In looking solely the datas splits, validation accuracy is expected to decrease from A to C, reflecting increasingly honest deployment estimates. However, it is worth noting upfront that Dataset B has the smallest training set at 412 samples, meaning that any lower performance observed may reflect reduced training data rather than stricter generalisation logic, which is to remain relevant as a limitation when interpreting the results."
