        "### Dataset B\n",
        "\n",
        "Dataset B splits the audio recording data by attempt numbers.\n",
        "\n",
        "Attempts 1 and 3 were selected for training while attempts 2 and 4 for validation, (instead of 1+2 vs 3+4) to ensure that both sets contain a representative mix of interpretation types (hum vs whistles).\n",
        "\n",
        "As confirmed by the data, attempts 3 and 4 consisted entirely of hum recordings (64 and 66 recordings respectively, and 0 whistles). A 1+2 vs 3+4 split would therefore result in a validation set with only hums, introducing a systematic interpretation bias. The 1+3 and 2+4 split avoids this by distributing both hums and whistles across both training and validation.\n",
        "\n",
        "It also ensures that no *exact same* audio is seen during the validation that has already been seen during the training.\n",
        "\n",
        "- Training set: 412 samples (attempts 1 & 3)\n",
        "\n",
        "- Validation set: 388 samples (attempts 2 & 4)\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "##### Limitation:\n",
        "\n",
        "In a case where (which more likely than not) a participant recorded attempts 1 and 2 in the same sitting, their vocal style / pitch type etc. may be very similar for both recordings, meaning the split may not test generalisation as needed."
