      "source": [
        "### Dataset C\n",
        "\n",
        "Dataset C is split by participant, and no one participant appears in over a single set, in any form. It is the strictest and most honest of real deployment conditions, and is the only dataset split that is uses to test.\n",
        "\n",
        "- Training set: 561 samples (130 participants)\n",
        "- Validation set: 161 samples (38 participants)\n",
        "- Test set: 78 samples (19 participants)\n",
        "\n",
        "The class distribution in the validation set is not evenly balanced, but it is reasonable enough, ranging from 15 to 27 recordings per song.\n",
        "\n",
        "The model is evaluated on audios it has never come across during training at all, and the test set is used only once at the end of Section 6, after the model selection and hyperparameter tuning stages are complete.\n",
        "\n",
        "##### Limitation:\n",
        "\n",
        "With only 19 test participants contributing 78 audio recordings, the test accuracy estimate carries more uncertainty than a larger test set would (Vabalas et al., 2019). Also, the test accuracy is likely less precise than the validation accuracy, due to the smaller sample size.\n",
        "\n",
        "However, and since the validation set was used to tune hyperparameters, it is no longer a fully independent estimate, making the test stage necessary to confirm performance on data that has had no influence on any model decision making.\n",
        "\n",
        "Additionally, the random assignment of participants to train and validation sets means results could still vary slightly with a different random (I,e if another participant was better/ more distinctive at humming/whistling within the feature space), the reported accuracy could also range accordingly."
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "dL0F2m2WSMZB"
      }
