      "source": [
        "---\n",
        "# 7 Conclusions\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "So, can this curated pipeline tell Necessities apart from New York when hummed  in the shower? Based on the results of this project...sometimes. Depending on which song, as we have seen.\n",
        "\n",
        "To look at the results literally, Necessities is misclassified as NewYork 0.24 of the time, yet NewYork is never misclassified as Necessities, suggesting Necessities has perhaps some more ambiguous musical characteristics in the feature space.\n",
        "\n",
        "The best validated pipeline (SVM, n_mfcc=13, C=0.5 on Dataset C), as justified throughout, achieved a validation accuracy of 0.3106. Intially, Random Forest had produced a higher validation accuracy at 0.3230, and the curated ensemble higher still at 0.3168. However, the seed variance analysis in Section 6.2 showed that Random Forest's validation accuracy fluctuated within our experiment by 0.0745 across random seeds (6x larger than the gap between RF and SVM at their defaults), which meant that the Random Forest 'advantage' there was not stable. SVM was therefore specifically selected as the final model, as the most reliable for tuning, and estimate for deployment quality.\n",
        "\n",
        "The final test accuracy on 19 entirely unseen participants and 78 recordings was 0.2308, lower than validation, as duly expected when the validation set has been used for hyperparameter tuning and is therefore no longer fully independent (Cawley and Talbot, 2010). The small test set of only 78 recordings across 8 classes also means that the estimate carries significant uncertainty. Ideally, we would require a larger test set. Despite this drop from validation accuracy, 0.2308 remains above random chance, confirming the pipeline extracts genuine signals even in a fully unseen participant setting.\n",
        "\n",
        "The 5 model ensemble underperformed compared to the best individual models, suggesting that Naive Bayes and kNN were most likely dragging the majority vote down, as the weakest performers. The curated ensemble of SVM, Random Forest and Logistic Regression produced the best validation accuracy at 0.3168. This very small margin difference suggests that the models have fairly similar patterns, and combining them does not truly offer much additional benefit.\n",
        "\n",
        "Cross-model confusion matrix analysis confirmed that the bottleneck is among the data and representation,  over model choice, with the same song pairs being consistently confused despite their very different decision boundaries.\n",
        "\n",
        "The most significant limitation is the time collapse of the features. Transforming a 10-second hum/whistle into a single mean vector discards much of the relevant information needed to tell apart how the melody progresses. If to conduct this experiment at a larger scale, Google's Hum to Search system could be used as example, by training a neural network to learn melody embeddings directly from spectrograms,and bypassing feature extraction as we have conducted entirely (Frank, 2020) allowing the model to learn what is distinct.\n",
        "\n",
        "Ultimately, it is worth acknowledging that the model is optimised for the empirical error surface of 561 training samples rather than the true population surface, meaning all reported accuracies are noisy estimates of real deployment quality.\n",
        "\n",
        "This project outlines the methodological challenges of small-sample audio classification and should not be mistaken for a final estimate of how any model would perform on the full population of hums and whistles."
      ]
    },
